#Text=Melbourne/Inner east
#Text=The inner east of Melbourne consists of a number of suburbs and localities within the Yarra municipality .
#Text=Compared with glitzy Stonnington on the other side of the river , the inner eastern area is known among Melburnians as a working-class district , filled with pubs and old factories .

#Text=Richmond is the home of many low price fashion stores and restaurants ; the northern area , centred on Victoria Street , is often called Little Saigon or Little Vietnam due to the huge number of Vietnamese food and shopping outlets .
#Text=South Richmond is well known for its low price fashion - along Bridge Road - and other wholesale outlets , mostly found along Swan Street .
#Text=Fitzroy is known as the Bohemian quarter of the city , with numerous trendy boutiques interesting restaurants .

#Text=Squeezed in the middle is Collingwood , a suburb that is not held to such a high esteem as the surrounding neighbourhoods , but still has its fair share of character-filled pubs and heritage-listed industrial buildings .
#Text=Abbotsford sits on the eastern fringe by the river , with some nice parkland among disused factories and breweries .
#Text=Get in
#Text=The inner east can be easily accessed by tram , train and road .
#Text=As far as public transport is concerned , all of the district lies within Zone 1 of Melbourne 's two fare zone structure .
#Text=See Melbourne 's Get around section for an explanation of the zone system and fares .
#Text=By tram
#Text=There are an abundance of trams in the district , as most routes must pass through in order to reach suburbs that are further out .
#Text=Major roads are listed along with the respective tram routes that traverse them .
#Text=Richmond
#Text=Victoria Street in North Richmond is served by trams 30 and 109 .
#Text=Tram 30 can be caught along La Trobe Street ( weekdays only ) while tram 109 can be caught along Collins Street in the City Centre .
#Text=Bridge Road is served by trams 48 and 75 .
#Text=The 48 operates along Collins Street and the 75 can be caught along Flinders Street in the City Centre .
#Text=Swan Street in the southern part of Richmond is served by tram 70 which can also be caught along Flinders Street in the City Center .
#Text=Church Street is the main north-south road in Richmond and is served by tram 78 .
#Text=The route begins at the intersection of Victoria Street and Church Street in North Richmond and travel south along Church Street which then becomes Chapel Street .
#Text=The tram terminates at Prahran in Stonnington .
#Text=They do not go into the City Centre .
#Text=Fitzroy
#Text=Gertrude Street is the major east-west thoroughfare in Fitzroy .
#Text=Tram 86 runs its length , before turning into Smith Street .
#Text=In the City Centre , it can be caught along Bourke Street .
#Text=The two end stations for this line are the Telstra Dome in the Docklands , and RMIT Bundoora campus .
#Text=Nicholson Street is a major north-south thoroughfare that borders the inner north district .
#Text=Tram 96 can be caught along Bourke Street in the City Centre .
#Text=The tram runs between St Kilda and West Brunswick .
#Text=Brunswick Street also runs north-south , closer to the centre of town .
#Text=It is served by tram 11 and can be caught along Collins Street in the City Centre .
#Text=The tram runs between Docklands and West Preston in the northern suburbs .
#Text=By train
#Text=Trains may be faster but they do not bring you to the heart of Richmond , mostly skirting the western edge of the suburb .

#Text=The exception is in the southern part of Richmond where trains on the Belgrave , Lilydale and Glen Waverly lines run parallel to Swan Street , which is served by Richmond ( all trains stop here ) , East Richmond ( which most trains skip ) and Burnley stations ( also skipped by many trains ) .
#Text=North Richmond is served by North Richmond station which is accessed from Victoria Street , whereas Bridge Road can be reached from West Richmond station .
#Text=While the stations are on both the South Morang and Hurstbridge lines , only the South Morang trains stop at both stations .
#Text=By bicycle
#Text=Bikes are the best way to get around a large part of the three inner city hubs of Collingwood , Fitzroy and Richmond .
#Text=Thanks to the ample bike lanes , biking is the fastest way to get around .
#Text=By bus
#Text=A number of frequent bus routes service areas not generally covered by tram or train services .
#Text=They are best used for east-west travel or for getting to the University of Melbourne .
#Text=Routes 200 and 207 operate every 10 minutes on Johnston St and Lygon Street ( weekdays ) from Melbourne Central in the CBD .
#Text=Routes 250 and 251 also operate along Rathdowne Street .
#Text=By road

#Text=Fitzroy can be easily reached from the City Centre via Nicholson Street , which connects to Spring Street in the eastern edge of the CBD , or Victoria Parade , which forms the southern border of the area .
#Text=Gertrude Street runs off Nicholson Street while Smith and Brunswick Streets run off Victoria Parade .
#Text=In the northern part of Fitzroy , both Brunswick Street and Smith Street intersect with Alexander Parade which leads on to the Eastern Freeway and the Eastern suburbs .
#Text=See
#Text=Bridge Road .
#Text=Within Richmond , it is most well known for its abundance of clothing factory outlets , which makes it a popular tourist attraction .
#Text=There are also many stores of up-and-coming local fashion designers .
#Text=Brunswick Street - Long and lively cafe/bar strip in Fitzroy with cheap and decent eats .
#Text=It 's a mixture of eclectic and interesting shops , clothes and food .
#Text=If street art is your thing , the surrounding alleyways and backstreets are also interesting , with an ever-changing array of graffiti , stencils and stickers on show .
#Text=Gertrude Street - Charming street of Fitzroy with cafes , bars , and unique clothing ( and other ) shops and art galleries .
#Text=It runs an after dark light show .
#Text=Centre of the local Aboriginal community .
#Text=Johnston Street - A street in Fitzroy , the western end is home of the local Hispanic community .
#Text=Many restaurants , bars and pubs , and the infamous Tote Hotel .
#Text=Smith St - Slightly run down yet charming street in Fitzroy with cafes , bars , and unique clothing ( and other ) shops .
#Text=Victoria Street - In North Richmond , the street contains a strip of Vietnamese restaurants and shops .
#Text=The heritage listed Foy & Gibson factory buildings in Oxford St.
#Text=Fitzroy Gardens and Conservatory .
#Text=Conservatory is open daily 9AM-5PM ( 5:30PM daylight savings ) .
#Text=Features a cafe and a conservatory amidst a lush garden setting .
#Text=Centre for Contemporary Photography , 404 George St , Fitzroy , ☏ +61394171549 , ✉ info@ccp.org.au .
#Text=W - Sa 11:00-6:0 ; Su noon-5PM .
#Text=Daily night projections after dark .
#Text=One of Australia 's premier venues for displaying contemporary photographic works .

#Text=Collingwood Children 's Farm , 18 St Heliers St , Abbotsford ( Buses 200 or 207 : Clarke St stop ; cross road and up Clarke St , left at St Heliers and at end of street . ) , ☏ +61394175806 , ✉ reception@farm.org.au .
#Text=9:15AM-4:30PM .
#Text=Perched on the banks of the Yarra River , the attraction 's aim is to provide a traditional country farm experience for city-dwellers .
#Text=A perennial favourite with kids , the farm allows visitors to unwind in the peaceful setting whilst interacting with a variety of farm animals .
#Text=Cow milking is held daily at 10AM and 4PM , and visitors can also cuddle animals such as guinea pigs , lambs and goats .
#Text=A café is on-site , and a lively farmer 's market is held on the second Saturday morning of each month .
#Text=$ 10 adults , $ 5 children/concessions , $ 20 families ( 2A+4C ) .

#Text=Abbotsford Convent , 1 St Heliers St , Abbotsford ( Buses 200 or 207 : Clarke St stop ; cross road and up Clarke St , left at St Heliers and on the right ) , ☏ +61394153600 , ✉ info@abbotsfordconvent.com.au .
#Text=7:30AM-10PM daily .
#Text=This site is host to a number of historic buildings which were originally home to sisters from a Christian religious order .
#Text=Traditionally associated with community service , the convent now houses a variety of community organisations , including restaurants , bars and two art galleries .
#Text=Many visitors simply enjoy the ambience of the grounds and soak up the building 's history .
#Text=Guided social history tours run every Sunday at 2PM for $15/person , but must be booked .
#Text=There are also occasional markets and rotating exhibitions .
#Text=Free entry .
